const BIOLOGY_AQA_PRACTICE = {
  'T1': {
    name: 'Biological Molecules',
    questions: [
      {q: 'Name the bond formed between two amino acids.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Peptide bond (1)'},
      {q: 'What type of reaction forms a glycosidic bond?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Condensation reaction (1)'},
      {q: 'State the monomer of starch.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Alpha-glucose (1)'},
      {q: 'Name the test used to detect proteins.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Biuret test (1)'},
      {q: 'What colour change indicates a positive result with Benedict\'s reagent?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Blue to brick red/orange (1)'},
      {q: 'Describe how a disaccharide is formed from two monosaccharides.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Condensation reaction between two monosaccharides (1). A glycosidic bond forms and water is released (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why lipids are good energy storage molecules.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'High ratio of hydrogen to oxygen atoms / more C-H bonds (1). More energy released per gram when oxidised compared to carbohydrates (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the structure of a phospholipid and explain how it forms a bilayer.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Glycerol bonded to two fatty acids and a phosphate group (1). Phosphate head is hydrophilic, fatty acid tails are hydrophobic (1). In water, phospholipids arrange with heads facing outward and tails inward forming a bilayer (1).'},
      {q: 'State two functions of water in living organisms.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Solvent for metabolic reactions / transport medium (1). Coolant through evaporation / temperature regulation due to high specific heat capacity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between alpha and beta glucose and its consequences for polysaccharide structure.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Alpha glucose has OH on C1 below the ring; beta glucose has OH on C1 above the ring (1). Alpha glucose forms coiled chains (amylose) or branched chains (amylopectin/glycogen) (1). Beta glucose forms straight chains in cellulose with H-bonds between chains forming strong microfibrils (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the quaternary structure of haemoglobin.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Four polypeptide subunits (2 alpha and 2 beta) (1). Each contains a haem group with an iron ion that binds oxygen (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how temperature affects enzyme activity.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Increasing temperature increases kinetic energy and rate of enzyme-substrate collisions (1). Above optimum, hydrogen bonds and ionic bonds maintaining tertiary structure break (1). Active site changes shape (denaturation) so substrate can no longer fit (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the emulsion test for lipids.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Dissolve sample in ethanol, then pour into water (1). A cloudy white emulsion forms if lipid is present (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the importance of hydrogen bonds in maintaining the structure of DNA.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Hydrogen bonds form between complementary bases holding the two strands together (A-T has 2, G-C has 3) (1). They are individually weak allowing strands to separate during replication/transcription but collectively strong enough to maintain the double helix (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the induced fit model of enzyme action.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Substrate enters the active site which is approximately complementary (1). The active site changes shape to fit closely around the substrate (1). This puts strain on the substrate lowering activation energy for the reaction (1).'},
      {q: 'A non-reducing sugar gave a negative result with Benedict\'s test. Describe how you would confirm it is a non-reducing sugar.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Boil the solution with dilute hydrochloric acid to hydrolyse the glycosidic bond (1). Neutralise the acid with sodium hydrogencarbonate (1). Re-test with Benedict\'s reagent - a positive result (blue to orange/red) confirms a non-reducing sugar was present (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why competitive inhibitors increase the apparent Km but do not affect Vmax.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Competitive inhibitors compete with substrate for the active site (1). Higher substrate concentration is needed to achieve half-maximum rate so apparent Km increases (1). At very high substrate concentration, substrate outcompetes the inhibitor so Vmax can still be reached (1).'},
      {q: 'State the difference between fibrous and globular proteins, giving one example of each.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Fibrous proteins have long, repetitive structures and are insoluble e.g. collagen (1). Globular proteins are spherical, compact and soluble e.g. haemoglobin/enzymes (1). Fibrous proteins have structural roles while globular proteins have metabolic/functional roles (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why enzymes have an optimum pH.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'At optimum pH, ionic and hydrogen bonds maintain the correct tertiary structure and active site shape (1). Above or below optimum, changes in H+ concentration alter charges on R groups (1). This disrupts ionic bonds and hydrogen bonds causing the active site to change shape so the substrate cannot bind (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of ATP in cells.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'ATP is the immediate energy source for cellular processes (1). It releases energy in small manageable amounts when hydrolysed to ADP and Pi by ATPase (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the structure of cellulose makes it suitable for its function in plant cell walls.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Beta-glucose monomers with alternating orientation form straight unbranched chains (1). Hydrogen bonds form between adjacent chains creating microfibrils (1). Microfibrils have high tensile strength (1). Layers of microfibrils at different angles provide strength in all directions preventing the cell from bursting when turgid (1).'},
      {q: 'A student mixed an enzyme with substrate at pH 2. No product was formed. Suggest and explain what happened.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enzyme was denatured at pH 2 (far from optimum) (1). Ionic bonds/hydrogen bonds maintaining tertiary structure were disrupted permanently changing active site shape (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why sucrose must be hydrolysed before it can be detected by Benedict\'s test.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Sucrose is a non-reducing sugar with no free anomeric carbon (1). Hydrolysis breaks the glycosidic bond releasing glucose and fructose which are reducing sugars that can reduce Cu2+ ions in Benedict\'s reagent (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would use a colorimeter to measure enzyme activity.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Set up the reaction with enzyme and substrate; take samples at regular time intervals (1). Use colorimeter to measure absorbance/transmission of the solution (1). Plot absorbance against time; the initial rate of change indicates enzyme activity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why water has a high specific heat capacity and why this is important biologically.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Many hydrogen bonds between water molecules require a lot of energy to break before temperature rises (1). This means large bodies of water have stable temperatures providing a constant environment for aquatic organisms (1). It also means body temperature of organisms does not fluctuate rapidly with changes in environmental temperature (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how amylose and amylopectin differ in structure and relate this to their roles in starch.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Amylose is a long unbranched chain of alpha-glucose with 1-4 glycosidic bonds forming a helix (1). It is compact and insoluble making it good for long-term storage (1). Amylopectin has 1-4 and 1-6 glycosidic bonds creating a branched structure (1). Many branch ends allow rapid hydrolysis by amylase when glucose is needed quickly (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by denaturation and why it is usually irreversible.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Denaturation is the permanent loss of the specific 3D/tertiary structure of a protein (1). The bonds maintaining the shape (H-bonds, ionic, disulfide) are broken and cannot reform correctly in the original pattern, so the active site is permanently altered (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the differences between DNA and RNA.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'DNA contains deoxyribose sugar while RNA contains ribose (1). DNA is double-stranded while RNA is single-stranded (1). DNA contains thymine while RNA contains uracil (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why non-competitive inhibitors reduce Vmax but do not affect Km.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Non-competitive inhibitors bind to an allosteric site causing a conformational change in the active site (1). Some enzyme molecules are permanently inactive regardless of substrate concentration so Vmax is reduced (1). The inhibitor does not compete with substrate for the active site so the affinity of remaining functional enzymes is unchanged and Km stays the same (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the significance of the cohesive property of water for transport in plants.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Hydrogen bonds between water molecules create cohesion forming a continuous column of water (1). This allows transpiration pull to draw water up the xylem without the column breaking (1).'},
      {q: 'State what is meant by activation energy and explain how enzymes reduce it.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Activation energy is the minimum energy needed for a reaction to occur (1). Enzymes provide an alternative reaction pathway with lower activation energy (1). The active site holds substrates in the correct orientation and/or puts strain on bonds, making the reaction more likely to proceed (1).'},
      {q: 'A student found that enzyme X had a Km of 5 mM and enzyme Y had a Km of 0.5 mM. Both catalyse the same reaction. Explain which enzyme has the greater affinity for the substrate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Enzyme Y has greater affinity for the substrate (1). Km is the substrate concentration at which the enzyme works at half its maximum rate; a lower Km means less substrate is needed to reach half Vmax indicating tighter binding/higher affinity (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a saturated fatty acid differs from an unsaturated fatty acid and the effect on the properties of lipids.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Saturated fatty acids have no C=C double bonds; unsaturated have one or more C=C double bonds (1). Double bonds create kinks in the hydrocarbon chain (1). Kinks prevent close packing so unsaturated fats are liquid at room temperature while saturated fats are solid (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why starch is a suitable storage molecule in plants.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Insoluble so it does not affect water potential / osmotic properties of the cell (1). Compact due to coiling (amylose) and branching (amylopectin) so large amounts can be stored (1). Easily hydrolysed to glucose when needed for respiration (1). Does not diffuse out of cells due to its large size / insolubility (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how a change in one amino acid could affect enzyme function.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The primary structure (amino acid sequence) determines the tertiary structure through R group interactions (1). A different amino acid may have different properties (charge, size, polarity) altering bonding patterns (1). This can change the shape of the active site so the substrate no longer fits / enzyme-substrate complex cannot form (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of water in hydrolysis reactions.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Water is added across the bond between monomers (1). This breaks the bond (glycosidic, peptide or ester) splitting the polymer into smaller units/monomers (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why glycogen is more branched than starch and the advantage of this.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Glycogen has more 1-6 glycosidic bonds creating more branches (1). More branch ends means more points for enzyme hydrolysis allowing rapid glucose release for high metabolic demand in animals (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the Biuret test procedure and expected results.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Add sodium hydroxide solution then copper sulfate solution to the sample (1). A purple/violet colour indicates protein is present (peptide bonds react with Cu2+ ions); blue indicates no protein (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why ice floating on water is biologically important.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ice is less dense than liquid water because hydrogen bonds form a regular lattice holding molecules further apart (1). Floating ice insulates the water below keeping it liquid so aquatic organisms can survive in winter (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the structure of a water molecule makes it an effective solvent.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Water is polar due to the electronegative oxygen atom creating partial charges (1). The partial charges attract and surround ions and polar molecules, dissolving them and enabling transport and metabolic reactions (1).'},
      {q: 'State what is meant by the tertiary structure of a protein and name three types of bond that maintain it.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Tertiary structure is the overall 3D shape of a single polypeptide chain due to interactions between R groups (1). Maintained by hydrogen bonds between R groups (1). Ionic bonds between charged R groups and disulfide bonds (covalent) between cysteine residues (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how you would investigate the effect of substrate concentration on the rate of an enzyme-catalysed reaction.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Prepare a range of substrate concentrations keeping enzyme concentration, temperature and pH constant (1). Mix enzyme with each substrate concentration and measure rate of product formation or substrate disappearance (1). Measure initial rate for each concentration e.g. using a colorimeter or gas collection (1). Plot a graph of rate against substrate concentration; expect rate to increase then plateau as all active sites become saturated (Vmax) (1).'},
      {q: 'A buffer was not used in an enzyme experiment. Explain how this could affect the results.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The reaction may produce acidic or basic products changing the pH of the solution (1). This could alter the ionisation of R groups in the enzyme, changing tertiary structure/active site shape and reducing the rate below the true value (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why cellulose cannot be digested by humans.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cellulose contains beta-1,4-glycosidic bonds (1). Humans lack the enzyme cellulase needed to hydrolyse these bonds so cellulose passes through the gut undigested as fibre (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of coenzymes in enzyme-catalysed reactions.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Coenzymes are non-protein organic molecules that bind temporarily to enzymes (1). They transfer chemical groups or atoms (e.g. hydrogen in the case of NAD) between enzyme-catalysed reactions, being recycled in the process (1).'},
      {q: 'A drug is described as an irreversible inhibitor. Explain how it differs from a reversible competitive inhibitor.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'An irreversible inhibitor binds permanently (covalently) to the enzyme and cannot be removed (1). A reversible competitive inhibitor binds temporarily to the active site and can be displaced by high substrate concentration (1). With irreversible inhibition, increasing substrate concentration does not restore activity; the enzyme is permanently inactivated (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the iodine test for starch, including the biochemical basis of the colour change.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Add iodine/potassium iodide solution to the sample; a blue-black colour indicates starch is present (1). Iodine molecules become trapped inside the helical structure of amylose producing the blue-black complex (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why proteins have a greater diversity of function than polysaccharides.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Proteins are made from 20 different amino acids with varied R group properties (charged, polar, non-polar, etc.) (1). The huge number of possible sequences and folding patterns produces diverse 3D shapes (1). This allows proteins to function as enzymes, antibodies, channels, receptors, structural components, hormones etc. while polysaccharides have mainly storage and structural roles (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe and explain what happens to enzyme activity as substrate concentration increases from zero.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'At low substrate concentration, rate increases proportionally as more substrate molecules are available to form enzyme-substrate complexes (1). As concentration increases further, rate of increase slows as fewer free active sites are available (1). At high concentration, all active sites are occupied (enzyme is saturated) and rate reaches Vmax (1). The enzyme concentration is now the limiting factor; adding more substrate does not increase rate (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why triglycerides are hydrophobic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The hydrocarbon chains of fatty acids are non-polar with no charge (1). They cannot form hydrogen bonds with water so triglycerides do not dissolve in water / are insoluble (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T2': {
    name: 'Cells',
    questions: [
      {q: 'State two features of prokaryotic cells not found in eukaryotic cells.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Circular DNA / no membrane-bound nucleus (1). 70S ribosomes / plasmids / cell wall made of peptidoglycan (any one) (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the actual size of a cell that appears 30mm on a micrograph at x1000 magnification.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Actual size = image size / magnification = 30mm / 1000 (1) = 0.03mm or 30 micrometres (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the function of the Golgi apparatus.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Modifies proteins by adding carbohydrate groups / lipids (1). Packages proteins into vesicles for secretion or transport to other organelles (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why cells placed in distilled water may lyse.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Distilled water has a higher water potential than the cell cytoplasm (1). Water enters by osmosis, the cell swells, and the membrane bursts (lysis) because animal cells have no cell wall to resist expansion (1).'},
      {q: 'State the difference between magnification and resolution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Magnification is how many times larger the image is compared to the actual object (1). Resolution is the minimum distance between two objects that can be distinguished as separate (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the structure of the cell membrane according to the fluid mosaic model.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Phospholipid bilayer with hydrophilic heads facing outward and hydrophobic tails inward (1). Proteins are embedded (intrinsic) or on the surface (extrinsic) in a mosaic pattern (1). Cholesterol is interspersed between phospholipids regulating fluidity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why electron microscopes have better resolution than light microscopes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Electrons have a much shorter wavelength than visible light (1). Resolution is limited by wavelength so shorter wavelength allows closer objects to be distinguished (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the steps of cell fractionation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Cells are homogenised (broken open) in cold isotonic buffered solution (1). The homogenate is filtered to remove debris (1). Ultracentrifugation at increasing speeds separates organelles by size/density; heavier organelles sediment first (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how facilitated diffusion differs from simple diffusion.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Facilitated diffusion uses channel or carrier proteins in the membrane (1). It allows passage of large or charged molecules that cannot cross the phospholipid bilayer directly, but still moves down a concentration gradient with no energy input (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why active transport is necessary for mineral ion uptake by root hair cells.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mineral ion concentration is higher inside root hair cells than in the soil solution (1). Ions must be moved against their concentration gradient which requires energy from ATP / active transport (1).'},
      {q: 'A plant cell is placed in a concentrated sucrose solution. Describe what happens.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Water leaves the cell by osmosis as the sucrose solution has a lower water potential (1). The vacuole shrinks and the cell membrane pulls away from the cell wall (plasmolysis) (1). The cell becomes flaccid as turgor pressure is lost (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of vesicles in the secretion of proteins.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Proteins are synthesised on ribosomes on the rough ER and transported in vesicles to the Golgi apparatus (1). The Golgi modifies and packages proteins into secretory vesicles (1). Vesicles move to and fuse with the cell membrane releasing contents by exocytosis (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why a TEM cannot be used to view living specimens.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Specimens must be very thin (sliced) and placed in a vacuum (1). The preparation process (fixing, dehydrating, staining with heavy metals) kills the cells (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the magnification of an image that is 40mm wide if the actual cell is 20 micrometres wide.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Convert units: 40mm = 40000 micrometres (1). Magnification = 40000/20 = x2000 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of cholesterol in cell membranes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cholesterol sits between phospholipids reducing their movement and membrane fluidity at high temperatures (1). At low temperatures it prevents phospholipids packing too closely together, maintaining membrane flexibility (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how endocytosis occurs.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The cell membrane invaginates (folds inward) around the substance to be taken in (1). The membrane pinches off forming a vesicle that moves into the cytoplasm containing the engulfed material (1).'},
      {q: 'A student used a light microscope with an eyepiece graticule to measure cells. Explain how the eyepiece graticule is calibrated.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Place a stage micrometer (with known scale divisions) on the stage (1). View both the stage micrometer and eyepiece graticule scales simultaneously (1). Count how many eyepiece divisions correspond to a known distance on the stage micrometer to calculate the actual size per eyepiece division (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the surface area to volume ratio decreases as cell size increases.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Volume increases as the cube of the linear dimension while surface area increases as the square (1). Therefore as cells grow larger, volume increases more rapidly than surface area reducing the ratio (1).'},
      {q: 'State two functions of the rough endoplasmic reticulum.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Provides a large surface area for ribosome attachment and protein synthesis (1). Transports newly synthesised proteins in vesicles to the Golgi apparatus for processing (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why water moves from a cell with a water potential of -200 kPa to a cell with a water potential of -500 kPa.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Water always moves from higher water potential to lower water potential by osmosis (1). -200 kPa is higher than -500 kPa so water moves from the first cell to the second cell (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe two differences between a SEM and TEM image.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'SEM shows 3D surface detail while TEM shows 2D thin section internal detail (1). TEM has higher resolution than SEM (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why mitochondria have their own DNA.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mitochondria are believed to have evolved from engulfed prokaryotes (endosymbiotic theory) (1). They retained some of their original circular DNA which codes for some mitochondrial proteins (1).'},
      {q: 'A cell is described as having many mitochondria, many ribosomes, and an extensive Golgi apparatus. Suggest and explain its function.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The cell is likely a secretory cell producing and exporting proteins (1). Many mitochondria provide ATP for active processes / protein synthesis / vesicle transport (1). Many ribosomes for high rate of protein synthesis; extensive Golgi for processing and packaging proteins for secretion (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why carrier proteins are needed for active transport but not for osmosis.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Active transport moves specific molecules against their concentration gradient requiring energy and a carrier protein to change shape (1). Osmosis is the passive movement of water through the phospholipid bilayer or aquaporins down a water potential gradient requiring no carrier protein or energy (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the process of co-transport of glucose in the ileum.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Na+/K+ ATPase on basal membrane pumps Na+ out of epithelial cell into blood creating low Na+ inside cell (1). Na+ diffuses from gut lumen into cell down its gradient via Na+/glucose co-transporter bringing glucose with it (1). Glucose concentration builds up inside the cell (1). Glucose moves out of cell into blood by facilitated diffusion through GLUT2 channels on basal membrane (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what happens to the rate of diffusion as the concentration gradient decreases.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Rate of diffusion decreases as the concentration gradient decreases (1). The driving force for net movement is the difference in concentration; as equilibrium is approached, net movement slows and eventually stops (1).'},
      {q: 'State what is meant by a totipotent cell.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A cell that can differentiate into any type of cell in the organism including extraembryonic/placental tissue (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why some drugs target membrane receptors.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Membrane receptors have specific shapes that bind signalling molecules/hormones (1). Drugs with complementary shapes can bind to these receptors to either activate or block them, altering cell signalling and function (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe two adaptations of epithelial cells lining the small intestine for absorption.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Microvilli increase the surface area for absorption of nutrients (1). Many mitochondria provide ATP for active transport of substances like glucose and amino acids (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the nuclear envelope has nuclear pores.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Nuclear pores allow mRNA to pass from the nucleus to the cytoplasm for translation at ribosomes (1). They also allow entry of substances needed in the nucleus such as nucleotides, RNA polymerase, and transcription factors (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a cell becomes specialised through differentiation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Different genes are switched on or off in the cell during development (1). Only specific genes are expressed producing particular proteins (1). This gives the cell its specialised structure and function e.g. red blood cells losing nucleus and filling with haemoglobin (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why glycoproteins on the cell surface membrane are important.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Glycoproteins act as antigens for cell-cell recognition by the immune system (1). They are also involved in cell signalling / receptor function for hormones and drugs (1).'},
      {q: 'A beetroot disc was placed in water at 20°C for 30 minutes. The water remained clear. Explain this observation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'At 20°C the cell membrane is intact with normal permeability (1). The red pigment (betacyanin) is contained within the tonoplast membrane of the vacuole and cannot leak out (1).'},
      {q: 'State two roles of the cytoskeleton.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Provides mechanical support and maintains cell shape (1). Involved in movement of organelles/vesicles within the cell and cell locomotion (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why plant cells do not burst in hypotonic solutions.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Water enters by osmosis making the cell turgid (1). The rigid cellulose cell wall resists further expansion and prevents bursting by exerting an inward pressure potential (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the difference between phagocytosis and pinocytosis.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Phagocytosis is the uptake of large solid particles (e.g. bacteria) by engulfing them (1). Pinocytosis is the uptake of fluids/dissolved substances in small vesicles from the cell surface (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why increasing temperature initially increases the rate of diffusion across a membrane.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Higher temperature gives molecules more kinetic energy so they move faster (1). This increases the rate of net movement across the membrane down the concentration gradient (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the evidence from cell fusion experiments that supports the fluid mosaic model.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Mouse and human cells were fused together at 37°C (1). Membrane proteins were labelled with different coloured fluorescent markers (1). Within 40 minutes the proteins had intermixed across the whole membrane surface showing that proteins move freely within the fluid bilayer (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the rate of active transport is affected by oxygen concentration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Active transport requires ATP (1). ATP is produced by aerobic respiration which needs oxygen; less oxygen means less ATP so active transport rate decreases (1).'},
      {q: 'A cell has a water potential of -300 kPa. It is placed in a solution with a water potential of -300 kPa. Describe what happens.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The solution is isotonic with the cell (same water potential) (1). There is no net movement of water because there is no water potential gradient (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why lysosomes have a single membrane.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The membrane keeps hydrolytic (digestive) enzymes separated from the rest of the cytoplasm (1). This prevents the enzymes from digesting the cell\'s own organelles and molecules (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would prepare a sample to view under a light microscope using a stain.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Cut a thin section of the tissue to allow light to pass through (1). Place on a glass slide and add a drop of stain (e.g. methylene blue for animal cells or iodine for plant cells) (1). Lower a coverslip at an angle to avoid trapping air bubbles, then view under the microscope (1).'},
      {q: 'State two differences between the rough endoplasmic reticulum and smooth endoplasmic reticulum.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Rough ER has ribosomes on its surface while smooth ER does not (1). Rough ER is involved in protein synthesis and transport while smooth ER synthesises lipids and steroids (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why viruses are not classified as living organisms.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Viruses are acellular (have no cell structure / organelles) (1). They cannot reproduce independently and must use host cell machinery to replicate (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how the Golgi apparatus produces lysosomes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The Golgi apparatus packages hydrolytic enzymes into vesicles (1). These vesicles bud off from the Golgi and become lysosomes containing digestive enzymes at low pH (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the advantage of compartmentalisation in eukaryotic cells.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Membrane-bound organelles create separate compartments with different internal conditions (pH, enzyme concentrations) (1). This allows incompatible reactions to occur simultaneously without interfering (1). It also increases surface area for membrane-bound reactions and concentrates substrates/enzymes for efficiency (1).'},
      {q: 'A student observed that more glucose was absorbed by intestinal cells when oxygen was available. Explain this observation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Glucose absorption uses co-transport which depends on the Na+ gradient maintained by the Na+/K+ pump (1). The Na+/K+ pump requires ATP from aerobic respiration which needs oxygen (1). Without oxygen less ATP is produced so the Na+ gradient is not maintained and less glucose is co-transported (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe two ways in which a prokaryotic cell differs from a eukaryotic cell in terms of genetic material.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Prokaryotes have a single circular chromosome not enclosed in a membrane; eukaryotes have linear chromosomes in a membrane-bound nucleus (1). Prokaryotes may have plasmids (small circular DNA molecules); eukaryotes do not normally have plasmids (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why increasing temperature beyond 40°C causes membranes to become more permeable.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'High temperatures increase kinetic energy of phospholipids making the bilayer more fluid with gaps (1). Membrane proteins (including channel and carrier proteins) denature as bonds maintaining their tertiary structure break (1). Permanent gaps form in the membrane allowing uncontrolled leakage of substances (1).'},
      {q: 'State the function of the centriole.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Organises the spindle fibres during cell division / mitosis and meiosis (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T3': {
    name: 'Organisms Exchange Substances',
    questions: [
      {q: 'State Fick\'s law of diffusion.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Rate of diffusion is proportional to (surface area x concentration difference) / diffusion distance (1).'},
      {q: 'Name two adaptations of alveoli for gas exchange.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Thin walls (one cell thick squamous epithelium) giving a short diffusion distance (1). Large total surface area from millions of alveoli / rich blood supply maintaining concentration gradient (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how ventilation maintains the concentration gradient for gas exchange in the lungs.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Breathing in brings fresh air with high O2 and low CO2 to the alveoli (1). Breathing out removes air with lower O2 and higher CO2, keeping the alveolar air different from blood, maintaining the diffusion gradient (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how the tracheal system in insects delivers oxygen to cells.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Air enters through spiracles on the body surface (1). It passes through tracheae which branch into smaller tracheoles (1). Tracheoles penetrate close to/directly contact respiring cells allowing diffusion over a very short distance (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why fish die if removed from water.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Gill filaments collapse without the support of water, greatly reducing surface area (1). The gills cannot ventilate in air and dry out, so gas exchange ceases (1).'},
      {q: 'Define tidal volume and vital capacity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Tidal volume is the volume of air breathed in or out during a normal breath at rest (1). Vital capacity is the maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after a maximum inhalation (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of surfactant in the alveoli.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Surfactant reduces surface tension of the thin film of moisture lining the alveoli (1). This prevents alveoli from collapsing during exhalation and makes it easier to inflate them during inhalation (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how the countercurrent system in fish gills maximises gas exchange.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Blood flows through gill lamellae in the opposite direction to water flow (1). This maintains a concentration gradient for oxygen along the entire length of the lamella (1). A greater percentage of available oxygen can be extracted compared to parallel flow (up to 80%) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why large organisms need a transport system but single-celled organisms do not.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Large organisms have a small surface area to volume ratio so diffusion alone is too slow (1). Distances from the surface to internal cells are too great for diffusion to supply oxygen/nutrients quickly enough (1). Single-celled organisms have a large SA:V ratio and short diffusion distances so diffusion is sufficient (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the apoplast pathway of water movement through the root.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Water moves through the cell walls and intercellular spaces (1). It does not cross any cell membranes; movement is driven by the water potential gradient across the root (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of the Casparian strip.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The Casparian strip is a band of suberin in the endodermis cell walls that is waterproof (1). It blocks the apoplast pathway forcing water through the symplast ensuring selective uptake of minerals and preventing backflow (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how stomata open.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Guard cells actively take up potassium ions lowering their water potential (1). Water enters guard cells by osmosis making them turgid (1). The thick inner cell wall causes the guard cell to bend outward opening the stomatal pore (1).'},
      {q: 'State three environmental factors that increase transpiration rate.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Higher temperature (increases kinetic energy of water molecules) (1). Lower humidity (increases water potential gradient between leaf and air) (1). Higher wind speed (removes humid air from leaf surface maintaining the gradient) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how water moves up the xylem according to the cohesion-tension theory.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Transpiration from leaves creates a negative pressure (tension) at the top of the xylem (1). Water molecules are pulled upward as a continuous column due to cohesion (hydrogen bonds between water molecules) (1). Adhesion between water and xylem walls helps support the column and prevents it breaking (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe two adaptations of xylem vessels for water transport.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'No end walls between cells creating continuous tubes for uninterrupted flow (1). Lignified walls provide strength to prevent collapse under negative pressure and make vessels waterproof (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by translocation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Translocation is the transport of assimilates (mainly sucrose and amino acids) (1) through the phloem from sources (e.g. leaves) to sinks (e.g. roots, fruits, growing points) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how sucrose is loaded into the phloem.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'H+ ions are actively pumped out of companion cells using ATP (1). H+ ions re-enter via co-transport proteins carrying sucrose with them into the companion cell (1). Sucrose passes into sieve tube elements through plasmodesmata (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why phloem transport is described as an active process.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Sucrose loading at the source requires ATP for H+ pumping by companion cells (1). Metabolic inhibitors stop phloem transport, confirming energy is required (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the structure of a sieve tube element and explain how it is adapted for transport.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Sieve tube elements have sieve plates (perforated end walls) allowing mass flow between cells (1). They have very few organelles and no nucleus to maximise space for flow (1). Companion cells provide ATP and proteins needed to maintain the sieve tube via plasmodesmata (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the Bohr effect.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'In respiring tissues CO2 production increases and pH decreases (1). Lower pH causes haemoglobin to change conformation reducing its affinity for oxygen (1). The oxygen dissociation curve shifts right so more oxygen is released to tissues with high metabolic demand (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the sigmoid shape of the oxygen dissociation curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'At low pO2 binding the first O2 is difficult as haemoglobin is in the tense state (1). Once the first O2 binds the shape changes (cooperative binding) making subsequent binding easier - steep part of curve (1). At high pO2 the curve levels off as haemoglobin becomes saturated with all four binding sites occupied (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why fetal haemoglobin has its dissociation curve to the left of maternal haemoglobin.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fetal haemoglobin has a higher affinity for oxygen than adult haemoglobin (1). This allows the fetus to take oxygen from maternal haemoglobin across the placenta where pO2 is relatively low (1).'},
      {q: 'A student investigated the effect of wind speed on transpiration using a potometer. Describe how the potometer works.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A cut shoot is sealed into a tube of water with an air bubble in a capillary tube (1). As the shoot transpires, water is taken up moving the air bubble along the scale (1). The distance moved per unit time gives the rate of water uptake as an estimate of transpiration rate (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the potometer measures water uptake rather than transpiration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Not all water taken up is lost through transpiration (1). Some water is used in photosynthesis and cell expansion/growth so water uptake slightly exceeds water loss (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe two adaptations of xerophytes for reducing water loss.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Thick waxy cuticle reduces evaporation from the leaf surface (1). Sunken stomata / rolled leaves / hairs trap moist air near the leaf surface reducing the water potential gradient driving transpiration (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the structure of the small intestine is adapted for absorption.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Villi increase the surface area for absorption (1). Microvilli on epithelial cells further increase surface area (1). Epithelium is one cell thick for short diffusion distance (1). Rich blood supply in the villus maintains concentration gradient; lacteals absorb fats (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why insects can be smaller than mammals but still achieve adequate gas exchange.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The tracheal system delivers air directly to cells via tracheoles so no circulatory system is needed for gas transport (1). Their small size means short diffusion distances from tracheoles to cells and a relatively large surface area to volume ratio (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how pulmonary ventilation rate is calculated and state its units.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Pulmonary ventilation rate = tidal volume x breathing rate (number of breaths per minute) (1). Units are dm3 min-1 or cm3 min-1 (1).'},
      {q: 'A patient with emphysema has reduced gas exchange. Explain why.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Alveolar walls are broken down reducing the total surface area available for gas exchange (1). The remaining tissue becomes less elastic so ventilation is less effective at maintaining concentration gradients (1). Increased diffusion distance as walls thicken with inflammation further reduces rate of gas exchange (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of elastic tissue in the lungs.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Elastic tissue stretches during inspiration as the lungs expand (1). During expiration it recoils passively helping to push air out and reduce lung volume without requiring energy (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe what happens during inspiration.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'External intercostal muscles contract raising the ribs up and out (1). Diaphragm contracts and flattens (1). These increase thorax volume, reducing air pressure in the lungs below atmospheric pressure causing air to flow in (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why carbon monoxide reduces oxygen transport.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Carbon monoxide binds irreversibly to haemoglobin at the oxygen binding site (forming carboxyhaemoglobin) with an affinity 250x greater than oxygen (1). This permanently reduces the amount of haemoglobin available for oxygen transport (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the mass flow hypothesis of phloem transport.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Sucrose is actively loaded into sieve tubes at the source lowering water potential (1). Water follows by osmosis from nearby xylem creating high hydrostatic pressure (1). At the sink sucrose is used/removed raising water potential so water leaves by osmosis (1). The difference in hydrostatic pressure between source and sink drives mass flow of solution through sieve tubes (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why blocking the phloem does not immediately stop xylem transport.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Xylem transport is driven by transpiration pull and cohesion-tension which are independent of phloem (1). Water continues to evaporate from leaves and be pulled up from roots regardless of whether sugars are being transported (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the relationship between surface area to volume ratio and metabolic rate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Smaller organisms have a larger surface area to volume ratio (1). They lose heat more rapidly requiring a higher metabolic rate per unit mass to maintain body temperature (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the structure of a root hair cell is adapted for its function.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Long hair-like extension increases surface area for water and mineral absorption (1). Thin cell wall and membrane provide short diffusion distance (1). Many mitochondria provide ATP for active transport of mineral ions against concentration gradients (1).'},
      {q: 'State two factors that affect the rate of water movement through the xylem.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Rate of transpiration/evaporation from leaves (1). Diameter of xylem vessels (wider vessels offer less resistance to flow) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the rate of transpiration is not constant throughout the day.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'During the day light causes stomata to open increasing transpiration (1). Temperature is usually higher during the day increasing evaporation rate (1). At night stomata close reducing transpiration to very low levels (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a ringing experiment provides evidence for phloem translocation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A ring of bark (containing phloem) is removed from around a tree trunk leaving the xylem intact (1). Tissue above the ring swells as sugars accumulate because phloem transport is blocked (1). Tissue below the ring dies as it no longer receives sugars/assimilates for respiration and growth (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the advantage of a double circulatory system over a single circulatory system.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Blood passes through the heart twice in one complete circuit maintaining higher pressure to the body (1). This allows faster delivery of oxygen and nutrients to respiring tissues compared to the low pressure after passing through the gas exchange surface in a single system (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the pulmonary ventilation rate if tidal volume is 0.5 dm3 and breathing rate is 15 breaths per minute.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'PVR = tidal volume x breathing rate = 0.5 x 15 (1) = 7.5 dm3 min-1 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the dissociation curve of myoglobin differs from haemoglobin and why.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Myoglobin curve is shifted to the left of haemoglobin showing higher oxygen affinity (1). This allows myoglobin to act as an oxygen store in muscle releasing oxygen only at very low pO2 during intense exercise when haemoglobin has already unloaded (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how the structure of the gill is adapted for gas exchange.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Many gill filaments and lamellae provide a large surface area (1). Lamellae are very thin (one or two cells thick) giving a short diffusion distance (1). Rich blood supply in lamellae maintains concentration gradient for oxygen uptake and CO2 removal (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why exercise increases the rate of oxygen delivery to muscles.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Increased heart rate and stroke volume increase cardiac output delivering more blood to muscles per unit time (1). Increased ventilation rate maintains steep oxygen gradient at the lungs for rapid loading (1). Bohr effect in active muscles (increased CO2/lower pH) shifts curve right increasing oxygen unloading (1).'},
      {q: 'State the difference between the apoplast and symplast pathways.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Apoplast pathway: water moves through cell walls and intercellular spaces, not crossing membranes (1). Symplast pathway: water moves through cytoplasm of cells connected by plasmodesmata, crossing the cell membrane only once (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the advantage of having haemoglobin rather than oxygen simply dissolved in plasma.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Haemoglobin greatly increases the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood (about 70x more than dissolved alone) (1). Its cooperative binding properties allow efficient loading at lungs and unloading at tissues in response to changing conditions (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how spiracles help insects conserve water.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Spiracles can be opened and closed by valves/muscles (1). Closing spiracles reduces water loss by evaporation from the tracheal system while still allowing periodic gas exchange (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why transpiration is sometimes described as a necessary evil.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Stomata must open for CO2 uptake for photosynthesis (which is essential) (1). However this inevitably allows water loss by transpiration which can cause wilting/dehydration if not balanced by uptake (1).'},
      {q: 'State two pieces of evidence that translocation in phloem is an active process.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Companion cells have many mitochondria providing ATP (1). Metabolic/respiratory inhibitors (e.g. cyanide) stop translocation (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T4': {
    name: 'Genetic Information Variation & Relationships',
    questions: [
      {q: 'Define the term gene.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A sequence of DNA nucleotides/bases that codes for a polypeptide (1).'},
      {q: 'State how many bases code for one amino acid.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Three bases (a triplet/codon) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by semi-conservative replication.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Each new DNA molecule contains one original (parent) strand and one newly synthesised strand (1). This was demonstrated by the Meselson-Stahl experiment using heavy nitrogen isotopes (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of DNA helicase in replication.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'DNA helicase unwinds the double helix (1). It breaks the hydrogen bonds between complementary base pairs separating the two strands (1).'},
      {q: 'State two differences between transcription and translation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Transcription occurs in the nucleus using DNA as a template; translation occurs at ribosomes in the cytoplasm using mRNA (1). Transcription produces mRNA; translation produces a polypeptide (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by a substitution mutation and its possible effects.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A substitution mutation is where one base is replaced by a different base in the DNA sequence (1). It may be silent if the new codon codes for the same amino acid due to degeneracy (1). It may cause a missense (different amino acid) or nonsense (premature stop codon) potentially altering the protein shape and function (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the process of transcription.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'RNA polymerase binds to the promoter region and unwinds a section of DNA (1). The template/antisense strand is read 3\' to 5\' (1). Free RNA nucleotides align by complementary base pairing (A-U, T-A, G-C, C-G) (1). RNA polymerase forms phosphodiester bonds between nucleotides producing a pre-mRNA strand which is processed and leaves through nuclear pores (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of tRNA in translation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'tRNA has a specific amino acid attached at one end (1). The anticodon on the tRNA is complementary to a specific codon on mRNA (1). tRNA carries its amino acid to the ribosome where the anticodon matches the codon ensuring the correct amino acid is added to the growing polypeptide chain (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how crossing over during meiosis produces genetic variation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'During prophase I homologous chromosomes pair up (form bivalents) and non-sister chromatids cross over (1). Sections of chromatids are exchanged between homologous chromosomes at chiasmata (1). This produces new combinations of alleles on each chromosome (recombinant chromosomes) that differ from both parents (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how independent assortment produces genetic variation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'During metaphase I homologous pairs line up randomly at the equator (1). The orientation of each pair is independent of others so different combinations of maternal and paternal chromosomes can end up in each gamete (2^n possible combinations where n = haploid number) (1).'},
      {q: 'Distinguish between a genotype and a phenotype.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Genotype is the genetic makeup/alleles present in an organism (1). Phenotype is the observable/measurable characteristics resulting from genotype and environmental interactions (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between continuous and discontinuous variation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Continuous variation shows a range of phenotypes with no distinct categories (e.g. height) controlled by many genes (polygenic) and environment (1). Discontinuous variation shows distinct categories with no intermediates (e.g. blood group) usually controlled by one or few genes (1). Continuous variation has a normal distribution; discontinuous variation can be represented by a bar chart (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why a frameshift mutation is likely to be more harmful than a substitution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A frameshift (insertion/deletion) changes every codon downstream from the mutation point (1). This alters most or all amino acids in the polypeptide from that point onward and may introduce a premature stop codon, completely changing protein structure and function (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would use the Hardy-Weinberg equation to determine carrier frequency.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Identify the frequency of homozygous recessive individuals from the population data (q2) (1). Calculate q by taking the square root, then p = 1 - q (1). Carrier frequency (heterozygotes) = 2pq (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how geographical isolation can lead to speciation.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'A physical barrier separates a population into two groups that cannot interbreed (1). Different selection pressures/environmental conditions in each area favour different phenotypes (1). Different alleles are selected for in each population changing allele frequencies independently (1). Over time sufficient genetic differences accumulate so that if brought together they can no longer interbreed to produce fertile offspring - they are now separate species (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by stabilising selection and give an example.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Stabilising selection occurs when individuals with intermediate phenotypes have highest fitness (1). Individuals at both extremes are selected against reducing phenotypic variation (1). Example: human birth weight - very large or very small babies have lower survival rates; average weight babies have highest survival (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the chi-squared test is used in genetics.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'It compares observed results with expected results based on a genetic ratio (null hypothesis) (1). Chi-squared = sum of (observed - expected)² / expected for each category (1). If the calculated value exceeds the critical value at p=0.05 the difference is significant and the null hypothesis is rejected (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the three-domain classification system.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Life is classified into three domains: Archaea, Bacteria, and Eukarya (1). Archaea and Bacteria are both prokaryotic but differ in cell wall composition and ribosomal RNA sequences (1). Eukarya includes all organisms with membrane-bound nuclei (protists, fungi, plants, animals) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why genetic drift has a greater effect in small populations.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In small populations random events (death, failure to reproduce) can significantly change allele frequencies by chance (1). In large populations random fluctuations average out so allele frequencies remain more stable (1).'},
      {q: 'Define species and explain one limitation of the biological species concept.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A species is a group of organisms that can interbreed to produce fertile offspring (1). Limitation: it cannot be applied to asexually reproducing organisms or fossils (1). Also some species can hybridise producing fertile offspring (e.g. some plants) challenging clear boundaries (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by codominance and give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Codominance is when both alleles are expressed equally in the heterozygote (neither is dominant) (1). Example: in ABO blood groups, alleles IA and IB are codominant producing AB blood type with both A and B antigens (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the founder effect and its consequences.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A small group of individuals colonises a new area carrying only a subset of the original population\'s alleles (1). The new population has reduced genetic diversity / different allele frequencies from the original (1). Rare alleles in the original population may be common in the new population, or common alleles may be absent (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why biodiversity is measured using an index of diversity rather than simply counting species.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Species richness alone does not account for the relative abundance of each species (1). An index of diversity considers both the number of species and the evenness of their distribution giving a more accurate picture of ecological diversity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the importance of courtship behaviour as a reproductive isolating mechanism.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Species-specific courtship displays ensure mating only occurs between members of the same species (1). This prevents hybridisation and maintains genetic integrity of each species (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the evidence for evolution from comparative DNA/protein sequencing.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Closely related species have more similar DNA/protein sequences than distantly related species (1). The number of differences in sequences is proportional to the time since species diverged (molecular clock) (1). This evidence is independent of morphological similarities and can reveal evolutionary relationships not apparent from physical features (1).'},
      {q: 'State what is meant by epistasis and describe its effect on phenotypic ratios.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Epistasis is when one gene masks/affects the expression of another gene at a different locus (1). In recessive epistasis a dihybrid cross gives a 9:3:4 ratio instead of 9:3:3:1 (1). In dominant epistasis it may give a 12:3:1 ratio because the epistatic gene prevents expression of the other gene (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why natural selection cannot act on genotype directly.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Natural selection acts on phenotype because it is the physical/observable characteristics that determine survival and reproduction (1). The genotype is selected indirectly through its effect on phenotype; alleles that produce favourable phenotypes increase in frequency (1).'},
      {q: 'A population of 1000 individuals includes 90 with the homozygous recessive phenotype. Calculate the frequency of the dominant allele.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'q2 = 90/1000 = 0.09 (1). q = √0.09 = 0.3 (1). p = 1 - 0.3 = 0.7 (frequency of dominant allele) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how antibiotic resistance in bacteria is an example of natural selection.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Random mutations produce alleles conferring antibiotic resistance in some bacteria (1). When antibiotics are applied, susceptible bacteria are killed but resistant ones survive (selection pressure) (1). Resistant bacteria reproduce passing resistance alleles to offspring (1). Over time the proportion of resistant bacteria in the population increases (change in allele frequency) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the difference between allopatric and sympatric speciation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Allopatric speciation involves geographical isolation separating populations physically (1). Sympatric speciation occurs within the same area without physical separation, often through polyploidy or behavioural/temporal isolation (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why meiosis is important for maintaining chromosome number across generations.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Meiosis produces haploid gametes (half the chromosome number) (1). When two haploid gametes fuse at fertilisation the diploid number is restored in the zygote (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the significance of random fertilisation in generating genetic variation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Any male gamete can fuse with any female gamete (1). Since each gamete is genetically unique (due to crossing over and independent assortment) the combination at fertilisation produces enormous variation in offspring genotypes (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would calculate Simpson\'s Index of Diversity.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Count the number of individuals of each species (n) and total individuals (N) in a sample (1). Calculate (n/N)² for each species then sum all values (1). D = 1 - Σ(n/N)²; a value close to 1 indicates high biodiversity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between genetic and environmental causes of variation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Genetic variation is caused by differences in DNA/alleles and is inherited (e.g. blood group) (1). Environmental variation is caused by external conditions and is not inherited (e.g. scars, accent); most phenotypic variation results from an interaction of both (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why two species cannot occupy the same ecological niche indefinitely.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'If two species have identical niches they compete for the same resources (competitive exclusion principle) (1). One species will inevitably be better adapted and outcompete the other which will be excluded from the habitat (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how linked genes affect the results of a dihybrid cross.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Linked genes are on the same chromosome so they tend to be inherited together (1). This means parental combinations appear more frequently than expected and recombinant types are rarer (1). The ratio deviates from 9:3:3:1; recombinants only arise from crossing over between the linked loci (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by the selection pressure in natural selection.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A selection pressure is an environmental factor that affects survival and reproduction (1). Examples include predation, disease, competition, or climate which cause differential survival of phenotypes (1).'},
      {q: 'State two assumptions of the Hardy-Weinberg principle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'No natural selection / all genotypes are equally fit (1). No mutation / no immigration or emigration / random mating / large population size (any one additional) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how polyploidy can lead to sympatric speciation in plants.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'An error in meiosis or mitosis produces an individual with extra sets of chromosomes (polyploid) (1). The polyploid cannot produce fertile offspring with diploid individuals due to uneven chromosome pairing in meiosis (1). If the polyploid can self-fertilise or reproduce vegetatively it establishes a new species in the same area (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the importance of the universal nature of the genetic code.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The same codons code for the same amino acids in almost all organisms (1). This provides evidence for a common ancestor / shared evolutionary origin, and allows genetic engineering between species as the code is read the same way (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a test cross is used to determine genotype.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'An organism showing the dominant phenotype (unknown genotype AA or Aa) is crossed with a homozygous recessive individual (aa) (1). If all offspring show the dominant phenotype the unknown parent is homozygous dominant (AA) (1). If approximately half show recessive phenotype the unknown parent is heterozygous (Aa) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why DNA base sequences are now preferred over physical characteristics for classification.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'DNA sequences provide objective measurable data not affected by convergent evolution or environmental variation (1). Physical similarities may be due to analogous structures (similar function but different origin) rather than shared ancestry (1). DNA comparisons can reveal evolutionary relationships that are not visible from morphology alone (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how mutation is the ultimate source of genetic variation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mutations create new alleles that did not previously exist in the gene pool (1). Without mutation all individuals would have identical alleles; meiosis and sexual reproduction shuffle existing variation but only mutation creates new variation (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of isolation in speciation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Isolation prevents gene flow between populations (1). This allows allele frequencies to change independently in each population due to different selection pressures and/or genetic drift (1). Over time reproductive incompatibility develops and two separate species form (1).'},
      {q: 'In a cross, 9/16 have purple flowers, 3/16 have red, 3/16 have blue, and 1/16 have white. Explain this ratio.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'This is a 9:3:3:1 ratio from a dihybrid cross between two heterozygous parents (AaBb x AaBb) (1). Two genes are involved in determining flower colour, each segregating independently (1). The different phenotype classes result from different combinations of dominant and recessive alleles at both loci (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why variation within a population is important for evolution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Variation provides different phenotypes for natural selection to act upon (1). If the environment changes, individuals with advantageous variations survive and reproduce passing alleles to the next generation allowing the population to adapt (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the evidence that mitochondrial DNA provides for human evolutionary relationships.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mitochondrial DNA is maternally inherited and does not undergo recombination (1). It has a relatively high mutation rate acting as a molecular clock; comparing mtDNA sequences between populations reveals migration patterns and evolutionary divergence times (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T5': {
    name: 'Energy Transfers',
    questions: [
      {q: 'State the net products of glycolysis from one molecule of glucose.', marks: 2, markScheme: '2 molecules of pyruvate (3C) (1). Net gain of 2 ATP and 2 reduced NAD (1).'},
      {q: 'Name the molecule that accepts CO2 in the Calvin cycle.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'RuBP (ribulose bisphosphate) (1).'},
      {q: 'State where the light-dependent reactions occur.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Thylakoid membranes of the chloroplast (1).'},
      {q: 'Name the enzyme that fixes CO2 in the Calvin cycle.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'RuBisCO (ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase) (1).'},
      {q: 'State the final electron acceptor in aerobic respiration.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Oxygen (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the link reaction.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Pyruvate (3C) moves from cytoplasm into the mitochondrial matrix (1). It is decarboxylated (CO2 removed) and dehydrogenated (hydrogen transferred to NAD forming reduced NAD) (1). The remaining 2C acetyl group combines with coenzyme A to form acetyl CoA (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of oxygen in aerobic respiration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Oxygen is the final electron acceptor at the end of the electron transport chain (1). It combines with electrons and H+ ions to form water; without it electrons would accumulate, the ETC would stop, and no ATP would be produced via oxidative phosphorylation (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe what happens during oxidative phosphorylation.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Reduced NAD and FAD donate electrons to the electron transport chain on the inner mitochondrial membrane (1). Electrons pass along a series of carriers releasing energy at each step (1). Energy is used to pump H+ ions from the matrix to the intermembrane space creating a proton gradient (1). H+ ions flow back through ATP synthase which catalyses ATP synthesis from ADP and Pi (chemiosmosis) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the inner mitochondrial membrane is highly folded.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cristae increase the surface area of the inner membrane (1). This provides more space for electron transport chain carriers and ATP synthase increasing the rate of oxidative phosphorylation (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the products of one turn of the Krebs cycle.', marks: 3, markScheme: '2 CO2 molecules are released by decarboxylation (1). 3 reduced NAD and 1 reduced FAD are produced by dehydrogenation (1). 1 ATP is produced by substrate-level phosphorylation (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why anaerobic respiration produces much less ATP than aerobic respiration.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Without oxygen the Krebs cycle cannot run and the electron transport chain is blocked (1). Only glycolysis occurs, producing just 2 ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation (1). The reduced NAD from glycolysis cannot be oxidised via the ETC so it is used to reduce pyruvate to lactate (or ethanol + CO2) to regenerate NAD so glycolysis can continue (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the light-dependent reactions of photosynthesis.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Light energy is absorbed by chlorophyll in PSII exciting electrons to a higher energy level (1). Electrons pass along an electron transport chain releasing energy used to pump H+ into the thylakoid lumen (1). Photolysis of water replaces electrons in PSII and releases O2 and H+ (1). Electrons from PSI reduce NADP with H+ to form reduced NADP; ATP is produced by chemiosmosis as H+ flows through ATP synthase (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the Calvin cycle.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'CO2 is fixed by RuBisCO combining with 5C RuBP to form 2 molecules of 3C GP (1). GP is reduced to TP (triose phosphate) using reduced NADP and ATP from light-dependent reactions (1). Most TP (5/6) is used to regenerate RuBP using ATP (1). 1/6 TP leaves the cycle and is used to make glucose and other organic molecules (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what a limiting factor is in photosynthesis.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A limiting factor is the factor present at the lowest/most limiting level that restricts the rate of photosynthesis (1). Increasing this factor increases the rate; once it is no longer limiting another factor becomes rate-limiting (e.g. light intensity, CO2 concentration, temperature) (1).'},
      {q: 'State the difference between cyclic and non-cyclic photophosphorylation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'In non-cyclic, electrons from PSII pass to PSI and then to NADP producing reduced NADP, ATP, and O2 from photolysis (1). In cyclic, electrons from PSI are recycled back to PSI via the ETC producing only ATP (1). Cyclic does not involve PSII, does not produce reduced NADP, and does not produce oxygen (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why increasing temperature beyond 40°C decreases the rate of the Calvin cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'RuBisCO and other enzymes in the Calvin cycle are denatured at high temperatures (1). Hydrogen bonds and ionic bonds maintaining their tertiary structure break so the active site changes shape and substrate cannot bind (1).'},
      {q: 'Define gross primary productivity and net primary productivity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'GPP is the total rate of energy fixation (biomass production) by photosynthesis (1). NPP = GPP - R (respiration by producers); it is the energy/biomass available to consumers (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why only about 10% of energy is transferred between trophic levels.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Energy is lost as heat during respiration at each level (1). Not all biomass is consumed - some organisms die without being eaten and are decomposed (1). Not all consumed biomass is digested/absorbed - energy is lost in faeces (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a respirometer can be used to measure the rate of respiration.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Organisms are placed in a sealed container with a CO2 absorber (e.g. KOH/soda lime) (1). As oxygen is consumed the volume of gas decreases moving a manometer fluid or bubble (1). The rate of oxygen uptake is measured over time; a control tube (dead/no organisms) accounts for temperature/pressure changes (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by the compensation point.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The compensation point is the light intensity at which the rate of photosynthesis equals the rate of respiration (1). At this point there is no net gas exchange as CO2 produced equals CO2 used, and O2 produced equals O2 used (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why decarboxylation reactions in respiration produce CO2.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Decarboxylation removes a carboxyl group from a substrate (1). This releases CO2 as a waste product (occurs in the link reaction and twice in the Krebs cycle) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of ATP in the Calvin cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'ATP provides energy for the regeneration of RuBP from triose phosphate (TP) (1). ATP also provides energy (along with reduced NADP) for the reduction of GP to TP (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what happens to the rate of photosynthesis when CO2 concentration increases at constant high light intensity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Rate increases because more CO2 is available for fixation by RuBisCO in the Calvin cycle (1). Eventually rate plateaus as another factor (e.g. amount of RuBisCO or light-dependent reaction products) becomes limiting (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the NPP if GPP is 20000 kJ m-2 yr-1 and plant respiration is 12000 kJ m-2 yr-1.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'NPP = GPP - R = 20000 - 12000 = 8000 kJ m-2 yr-1 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why reduced NAD is described as having a high energy value.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Reduced NAD carries hydrogen atoms (electrons and protons) with high energy (1). When electrons pass through the ETC they release energy used to make approximately 2.5 ATP per NADH (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of photolysis in the light-dependent reactions.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Photolysis splits water molecules using light energy (2H2O → 4H+ + 4e- + O2) (1). The electrons replace those lost from PSII chlorophyll, H+ ions contribute to the proton gradient and reduce NADP, and oxygen is released as a by-product (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe substrate-level phosphorylation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'ATP is produced by direct transfer of a phosphate group from a phosphorylated substrate to ADP (1). It occurs in glycolysis and the Krebs cycle without the electron transport chain (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why glucose must be phosphorylated at the start of glycolysis.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Phosphorylation activates glucose making it more reactive / lowers activation energy for subsequent reactions (1). It also prevents glucose from leaving the cell (charged molecule cannot cross membrane) and destabilises the molecule for splitting into two triose phosphate molecules (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the effect of a respiratory inhibitor like cyanide on ATP production.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Cyanide blocks cytochrome c oxidase (the last electron carrier in the ETC) (1). Electrons cannot pass to oxygen so the whole ETC stops (1). H+ ions are not pumped, the proton gradient collapses, and ATP synthase stops producing ATP by oxidative phosphorylation (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would investigate the effect of light intensity on the rate of photosynthesis using an aquatic plant.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Place an aquatic plant (e.g. Elodea) in water with NaHCO3 (as CO2 source) under a lamp (1). Vary light intensity by changing distance of lamp from plant (inverse square law) (1). Count bubbles of oxygen produced per unit time or collect gas in a syringe (1). Repeat at each distance; control temperature using a water bath/heat shield (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by the respiratory quotient (RQ) and calculate it for glucose.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'RQ = CO2 produced / O2 consumed (1). For glucose (C6H12O6): 6CO2/6O2 = 1.0 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the RQ for fats is less than 1.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fats have proportionally more hydrogen atoms and fewer oxygen atoms than carbohydrates (1). More oxygen is needed for oxidation relative to CO2 produced so O2 consumed > CO2 produced giving RQ < 1 (typically ~0.7) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how energy from light is used to produce ATP in the thylakoid membrane.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Light excites electrons in chlorophyll to higher energy levels (1). Excited electrons pass along carriers in the thylakoid membrane losing energy at each step (1). This energy pumps H+ into the thylakoid lumen; H+ flows out through ATP synthase producing ATP (photophosphorylation) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why increasing temperature from 10 to 30°C increases the rate of the Calvin cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Higher temperature increases kinetic energy of molecules (enzyme and substrate) (1). More frequent and energetic collisions between RuBisCO (and other enzymes) and substrates increase the rate of enzyme-catalysed reactions (1).'},
      {q: 'State two uses of triose phosphate (TP) produced in the Calvin cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'TP can be converted to glucose/sucrose/starch for storage or transport (1). TP can also be used to synthesise amino acids (with nitrogen source), lipids, or nucleotides, or regenerated to RuBP (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between photophosphorylation and oxidative phosphorylation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Photophosphorylation occurs in thylakoid membranes using light energy to drive electron flow and ATP synthesis (1). Oxidative phosphorylation occurs on the inner mitochondrial membrane using energy from oxidation of reduced coenzymes (NADH/FADH2) from respiration (1).'},
      {q: 'A plant is placed in darkness. Describe what happens to the concentrations of GP and RuBP.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'GP concentration increases because it cannot be reduced to TP without reduced NADP and ATP from the light reactions (1). RuBP concentration decreases because it is still used to fix CO2 but cannot be regenerated (requires ATP) from TP (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why farming practices that remove biomass require addition of fertilisers.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Harvesting removes minerals (nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium etc.) locked in plant biomass from the ecosystem (1). Without decomposition to return these minerals to the soil, nutrient depletion would reduce crop growth; fertilisers replace these lost minerals (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of acetyl CoA in respiration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Acetyl CoA is produced from pyruvate in the link reaction (1). It enters the Krebs cycle by combining with 4-carbon oxaloacetate to form 6-carbon citrate, feeding carbon atoms into the cycle for oxidation (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why a graph of rate of photosynthesis against light intensity shows a plateau.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'At low to moderate light intensity, light is limiting so rate increases proportionally (1). At high intensity, another factor (CO2 concentration or temperature/enzyme activity) becomes limiting so the rate cannot increase further (plateau) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the biological significance of ATP being readily hydrolysed.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The hydrolysis of ATP to ADP + Pi releases a small manageable amount of energy suitable for driving individual cellular reactions (1). This avoids wasteful release of large amounts of energy as heat and allows precise control of energy use (1).'},
      {q: 'State two differences between the electron transport chain in photosynthesis and respiration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In photosynthesis it is located on thylakoid membranes; in respiration on the inner mitochondrial membrane (1). In photosynthesis electrons come from photoactivated chlorophyll; in respiration electrons come from reduced NAD/FAD (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why DNP (dinitrophenol) causes weight loss.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'DNP makes the inner mitochondrial membrane permeable to H+ ions (1). H+ ions leak back to the matrix bypassing ATP synthase so the proton gradient is dissipated as heat rather than making ATP (1). Cells must oxidise more substrate (fat/glucose) to make enough ATP to survive, causing weight loss but dangerously increasing body temperature (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would use a DCPIP experiment to show that isolated chloroplasts carry out light-dependent reactions.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Add blue DCPIP solution to a suspension of isolated chloroplasts (1). Expose to light and observe that DCPIP changes from blue to colourless as it is reduced (accepts electrons from the photosystems) (1). A control tube kept in the dark remains blue showing light is required for the reduction (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the percentage efficiency of energy transfer if 5000 kJ enters a trophic level and 450 kJ is incorporated into new biomass.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Efficiency = (energy incorporated / energy available) x 100 (1). = (450/5000) x 100 = 9% (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of FAD in the Krebs cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'FAD accepts hydrogen atoms (2H) from succinate during one dehydrogenation step in the Krebs cycle to become reduced FAD (FADH2) (1). Reduced FAD donates electrons to the ETC (at a lower entry point than NADH) contributing to the proton gradient for ATP synthesis (produces approximately 1.5 ATP) (1).'},
      {q: 'A farmer uses a greenhouse to increase crop yield. Explain how controlling CO2 concentration and temperature increases photosynthesis.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Elevated CO2 concentration (e.g. from burning propane) increases the rate of carbon fixation by RuBisCO in the Calvin cycle (1). Maintaining optimal temperature ensures enzymes work at maximum rate without denaturation (1). Removing CO2 and temperature as limiting factors means light becomes the main limiting factor which can also be supplemented (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why coenzyme A is described as a coenzyme and not an enzyme.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Coenzyme A is a non-protein organic molecule that assists enzyme function but is not itself a catalyst (1). It temporarily carries the acetyl group produced in the link reaction to the Krebs cycle, acting as a transferring molecule rather than speeding up a specific reaction (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how energy flows through an ecosystem.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Light energy is converted to chemical energy by photosynthesis in producers (1). Energy passes to consumers through feeding at each trophic level (1). At each level energy is lost as heat through respiration; decomposers release remaining energy from dead matter, so energy flows through (not recycled within) the ecosystem (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T6': {
    name: 'Organisms Respond to Changes',
    questions: [
      {q: 'State what is meant by a stimulus.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A detectable change in the internal or external environment that produces a response (1).'},
      {q: 'Name the neurotransmitter released at a cholinergic synapse.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Acetylcholine (ACh) (1).'},
      {q: 'State the role of the myelin sheath.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Electrical insulation that speeds up nerve impulse transmission by saltatory conduction (1).'},
      {q: 'Define homeostasis.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The maintenance of a constant/stable internal environment (1) despite changes in external conditions (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of insulin in blood glucose regulation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Insulin is released by beta cells in the islets of Langerhans when blood glucose is high (1). It stimulates uptake of glucose by cells via GLUT4 transporters (1). It promotes glycogenesis (conversion of glucose to glycogen) in liver and muscle cells, lowering blood glucose (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what happens during repolarisation of a neurone.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Voltage-gated sodium channels close and voltage-gated potassium channels open (1). K+ ions diffuse out of the axon down their concentration gradient restoring the negative resting potential (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the structure of a sarcomere.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A sarcomere extends from one Z-line to the next (1). It contains thin actin filaments attached to Z-lines and thick myosin filaments in the centre (1). The I-band contains only actin, the A-band spans the length of myosin, and the H-zone contains only myosin (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the refractory period is important.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'It ensures action potentials travel in one direction only as the region behind cannot be re-stimulated (1). It also limits the frequency of impulses ensuring discrete separate signals (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a nerve impulse is transmitted across a synapse.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Action potential arrives at presynaptic knob causing Ca2+ channels to open and Ca2+ to enter (1). Ca2+ causes synaptic vesicles to fuse with presynaptic membrane releasing neurotransmitter by exocytosis (1). Neurotransmitter diffuses across the synaptic cleft and binds to receptors on the postsynaptic membrane (1). This opens Na+ channels causing depolarisation; if threshold is reached an action potential is generated in the postsynaptic neurone (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Sympathetic system prepares the body for activity (fight or flight) increasing heart rate and blood pressure (1). Parasympathetic system promotes rest and digestion decreasing heart rate; the two systems are antagonistic (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the sliding filament model accounts for muscle contraction.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Ca2+ from sarcoplasmic reticulum binds troponin causing tropomyosin to move exposing binding sites on actin (1). Myosin heads bind to actin forming cross-bridges (1). ATP hydrolysis causes the power stroke - myosin head pivots pulling actin toward the centre of the sarcomere (1). ATP then binds to myosin causing detachment and the head is re-cocked; repeated cycles shorten the sarcomere (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why skeletal muscles work in antagonistic pairs.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Muscles can only contract (pull) and cannot actively extend/push (1). An opposing muscle is needed to reverse the movement e.g. biceps contracts to flex the arm, triceps contracts to extend it (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of glucagon in blood glucose regulation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Glucagon is released by alpha cells in the islets of Langerhans when blood glucose is low (1). It stimulates glycogenolysis (breakdown of glycogen to glucose) in the liver (1). It also stimulates gluconeogenesis (formation of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources) raising blood glucose (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how saltatory conduction increases the speed of nerve impulses.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The myelin sheath insulates the axon so depolarisation can only occur at nodes of Ranvier (gaps in myelin) (1). The action potential jumps from node to node which is much faster than continuous conduction along an unmyelinated axon (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of calcium ions in synaptic transmission.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When an action potential arrives at the presynaptic knob voltage-gated calcium channels open (1). Ca2+ influx triggers fusion of synaptic vesicles with the membrane releasing neurotransmitter into the cleft (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why acetylcholinesterase is important at synapses.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Acetylcholinesterase breaks down acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft (1). This prevents continuous stimulation of the postsynaptic membrane and allows the synapse to reset for the next impulse (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how negative feedback controls blood glucose after a meal.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'After a meal blood glucose rises above the set point (1). Beta cells in the pancreas detect the rise and secrete insulin (1). Insulin stimulates glucose uptake by cells and glycogenesis reducing blood glucose (1). As glucose returns to normal insulin secretion decreases - the response reverses the original deviation (negative feedback) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what happens during the hyperpolarisation phase of an action potential.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'K+ channels remain open slightly too long causing excess K+ efflux (1). The membrane potential becomes more negative than resting potential (below -70mV) before the K+ channels close and the Na+/K+ pump restores resting potential (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how phototropism occurs in a plant shoot.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Light is detected by photoreceptors and causes auxin to redistribute to the shaded side of the shoot (1). Higher auxin concentration on the shaded side stimulates cell elongation there (1). The shaded side grows faster causing the shoot to bend toward the light (positive phototropism) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of the SAN (sinoatrial node) in controlling heart rate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The SAN is the pacemaker that generates electrical impulses initiating each heartbeat (1). It sets the basic rhythm of contraction which can be modified by sympathetic/parasympathetic nerves from the medulla (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a generator potential is produced in a Pacinian corpuscle.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Pressure deforms the lamellae surrounding the sensory nerve ending (1). The membrane of the nerve ending is stretched opening stretch-mediated Na+ channels (1). Na+ ions enter the cell causing localised depolarisation (generator potential); if threshold is reached an action potential is triggered (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between Type I and Type II diabetes.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Type I: autoimmune destruction of beta cells means no/insufficient insulin is produced (1). Type II: cells become resistant to insulin so glucose uptake is reduced even though insulin is still produced (1). Type I requires insulin injections; Type II is managed by diet, exercise, and medication (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by temporal summation at a synapse.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A single presynaptic neurone fires multiple action potentials in rapid succession (1). Neurotransmitter accumulates in the cleft before being broken down, summing to reach threshold in the postsynaptic membrane (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of ATP in muscle relaxation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'ATP binds to the myosin head causing it to detach from actin (breaking the cross-bridge) (1). Without ATP (e.g. after death) myosin remains bound to actin resulting in rigor (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the medulla oblongata controls breathing rate.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The ventilation centre in the medulla sends rhythmic impulses to the intercostal muscles and diaphragm controlling basic breathing rate (1). Chemoreceptors detect changes in blood CO2/pH and send signals to the medulla (1). High CO2/low pH increases impulse frequency to respiratory muscles increasing breathing rate and depth (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why positive feedback is less common than negative feedback.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Positive feedback amplifies a change moving further from the set point (1). This is destabilising and only useful in specific situations (e.g. blood clotting, labour contractions) where a rapid completion of a process is needed; it would be harmful for maintaining steady states (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of the sarcoplasmic reticulum in muscle contraction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The sarcoplasmic reticulum stores calcium ions at rest (1). When stimulated by an action potential it releases Ca2+ into the sarcoplasm triggering the sliding filament mechanism (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how slow-twitch and fast-twitch muscle fibres differ in their properties.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Slow-twitch fibres have many mitochondria and rich blood supply for sustained aerobic respiration; they resist fatigue (1). Fast-twitch fibres have fewer mitochondria but large glycogen stores for rapid anaerobic respiration generating quick powerful contractions (1). Slow-twitch appear red (myoglobin); fast-twitch appear white (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how baroreceptors help control blood pressure.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Baroreceptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch detect changes in blood pressure (1). If blood pressure rises they send more impulses to the cardiovascular centre in the medulla (1). The medulla increases parasympathetic output decreasing heart rate and reducing blood pressure (negative feedback) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of gibberellin in seed germination.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'When seeds absorb water the embryo produces gibberellin (1). Gibberellin diffuses to the aleurone layer and activates genes for amylase production (1). Amylase hydrolyses starch reserves to maltose/glucose providing energy and substrates for growth of the embryo (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what happens at a neuromuscular junction.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'An action potential arrives at the motor neurone terminal causing Ca2+ influx and ACh release (1). ACh binds to nicotinic receptors on the motor end plate of the muscle fibre causing Na+ channels to open (1). Depolarisation of the muscle cell membrane triggers release of Ca2+ from SR initiating contraction (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the importance of the all-or-nothing principle for information transmission.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'All action potentials are the same size regardless of stimulus strength ensuring signal is not degraded over distance (1). Stimulus intensity is coded by frequency of impulses and number of neurones firing rather than signal amplitude (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how the body responds to a decrease in core body temperature.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Thermoreceptors detect the drop and send impulses to the hypothalamus (1). Vasoconstriction of skin arterioles reduces blood flow to the surface decreasing heat loss (1). Shivering (involuntary muscle contractions) generates heat (1). Metabolic rate may increase; hair erector muscles contract (less effective in humans) to trap insulating air (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the knee-jerk reflex only involves two neurones.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'It is a monosynaptic reflex with only a sensory neurone synapsing directly with a motor neurone (no relay neurone) (1). This minimises the number of synapses reducing the time for the response making it very fast for protective purposes (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how inhibitory synapses work.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Inhibitory neurotransmitter (e.g. GABA) binds to receptors on the postsynaptic membrane (1). This opens Cl- channels (Cl- enters) or K+ channels (K+ leaves) causing hyperpolarisation (IPSP) making it harder to reach threshold (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why adrenaline affects heart rate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Adrenaline binds to receptors on the SAN cells (1). This increases the rate of depolarisation in the SAN increasing heart rate to supply more oxygen and glucose to muscles during fight or flight (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of tropomyosin in muscle contraction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'At rest tropomyosin covers the myosin-binding sites on actin preventing cross-bridge formation (1). When Ca2+ binds to troponin the tropomyosin moves to expose the binding sites allowing contraction to occur (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the pupil reflex is an example of a reflex arc.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Receptor: photoreceptors in the retina detect bright light (1). Coordinator: impulses are sent via sensory neurones to the brain which processes and sends impulses via parasympathetic motor neurones (1). Effector: circular muscles of the iris contract causing the pupil to constrict reducing light entry (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the advantage of a reflex response being involuntary and rapid.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Being involuntary means no conscious thought is needed so the response is not slowed by processing time (1). Rapid responses protect the body from harm before damage occurs e.g. withdrawing hand from hot object (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how insulin resistance develops in Type II diabetes.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Chronic high blood glucose and/or obesity leads to sustained high insulin levels (1). Target cells downregulate insulin receptors or their signalling pathways become desensitised (1). Cells no longer respond effectively to insulin so glucose is not taken up, keeping blood glucose elevated despite insulin presence (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of second messengers in hormone action.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Protein/peptide hormones cannot cross the cell membrane so they bind to membrane receptors (1). Binding activates an enzyme (adenylyl cyclase) on the inner surface which converts ATP to cAMP (second messenger) (1). cAMP activates protein kinases inside the cell which trigger a cascade of reactions producing the cellular response (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why steroid hormones and protein hormones have different mechanisms of action.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Steroid hormones are lipid-soluble so they can pass directly through the phospholipid bilayer of the cell membrane (1). They bind to intracellular receptors and the hormone-receptor complex acts as a transcription factor directly affecting gene expression (1). Protein hormones are water-soluble and cannot cross the membrane so they use membrane receptors and second messenger systems (cAMP) to produce effects intracellularly (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why damage to the hypothalamus could affect body temperature regulation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The hypothalamus is the thermoregulatory centre that receives input from thermoreceptors and compares blood temperature with the set point (1). Without it the body cannot detect deviation from normal or coordinate responses (vasoconstriction, shivering, sweating) to correct temperature changes (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the sequence of events during a single cross-bridge cycle.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Myosin head (energised by ATP hydrolysis) binds to exposed site on actin forming a cross-bridge (1). The myosin head pivots (power stroke) pulling actin toward the M-line / centre of sarcomere (1). A new ATP molecule binds to the myosin head causing it to detach from actin (1). ATP is hydrolysed to ADP + Pi re-cocking the myosin head ready for the next cycle (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the heart has its own blood supply via coronary arteries.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cardiac muscle contracts continuously requiring a constant supply of oxygen and glucose for aerobic respiration (1). The blood flowing through the chambers cannot supply the thick heart wall sufficiently so coronary arteries deliver oxygenated blood directly to the myocardium (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how auxin causes different responses in roots compared to shoots.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'High auxin concentration promotes cell elongation in shoots (positive effect) (1). The same concentration inhibits cell elongation in roots which are more sensitive to auxin; in gravitropism auxin accumulates on the lower side inhibiting root growth there causing downward bending (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how the body responds to high blood glucose after a meal.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Beta cells in the islets of Langerhans detect the rise in blood glucose (1). They secrete insulin into the blood (1). Insulin binds to receptors on liver and muscle cells stimulating glucose uptake via GLUT4 channels and glycogenesis (glucose → glycogen) reducing blood glucose back to normal (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why sensory adaptation occurs with constant stimulation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'With sustained constant stimulus the receptor generates fewer action potentials over time (1). This prevents overstimulation of the nervous system and allows attention to be focused on new/changing stimuli rather than constant background signals (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how spatial summation allows integration of information.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Multiple presynaptic neurones release small amounts of neurotransmitter onto one postsynaptic neurone simultaneously (1). Individual inputs may be subthreshold but their combined effect can reach threshold; this allows the nervous system to integrate signals from multiple sources before generating a response (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T7': {
    name: 'Genetics Populations Evolution & Ecosystems',
    questions: [
      {q: 'Define the term ecosystem.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A community of organisms and their abiotic (non-living) environment interacting together (1).'},
      {q: 'State what is meant by a trophic level.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The position of an organism in a food chain / its feeding level (1).'},
      {q: 'Name the process by which nitrogen gas is converted to ammonia by bacteria.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Nitrogen fixation (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of nitrifying bacteria in the nitrogen cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Nitrifying bacteria oxidise ammonium ions (NH4+) to nitrite (NO2-) and then to nitrate (NO3-) (1). This is nitrification and occurs in aerobic soil conditions making nitrogen available for plant uptake (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why decomposers are essential for nutrient cycling.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Decomposers break down dead organic matter and waste products (1). This releases minerals/inorganic ions (e.g. NH4+, PO4 3-) back into the soil making them available for plant absorption (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe primary succession on bare rock.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Pioneer species (e.g. lichens) colonise bare rock; they can withstand harsh conditions (1). They weather rock and produce organic matter creating thin soil when they die (1). This allows colonisation by mosses, then grasses, then shrubs, each seral stage modifying conditions (1). Eventually a climax community (e.g. woodland) develops which is stable and self-sustaining (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between primary and secondary succession.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Primary succession begins on previously uncolonised bare substrate with no soil (e.g. volcanic rock) (1). Secondary succession occurs on land where a community has been disrupted but soil remains (e.g. after fire), so it proceeds faster (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why energy cannot be recycled in an ecosystem.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Energy enters as light and is converted to chemical energy, then lost as heat at each trophic level during respiration (1). Heat energy cannot be converted back to usable chemical energy and dissipates to the surroundings (second law of thermodynamics) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would use quadrats to estimate population size of a plant species.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Place quadrats randomly in the study area (use random number generator for coordinates) (1). Count the number of target species in each quadrat (1). Calculate mean per quadrat then multiply by total area/quadrat area to estimate total population (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the mark-release-recapture method.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Capture a sample of animals, count them (n1), mark them harmlessly, and release them (1). After time for mixing, capture a second sample (n2) and count marked individuals (nm) (1). Estimate population: N = (n1 × n2) / nm (Lincoln Index) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why populations show a carrying capacity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'As population grows resources (food, space, mates) become limited (1). Intraspecific competition increases causing birth rate to decrease and death rate to increase until they are equal, stabilising population at carrying capacity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the effect of interspecific competition on population size.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When two species compete for the same limited resources both populations are smaller than they would be alone (1). If one species is a better competitor it may exclude the other (competitive exclusion) or both may adapt to use slightly different resources (niche partitioning) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe predator-prey relationships and their effect on population cycles.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'As prey population increases more food is available for predators so predator numbers increase (1). More predators means more prey are eaten so prey population decreases (1). With less prey predator numbers decline allowing prey to recover; this creates oscillating population cycles with predator peaks lagging behind prey peaks (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how eutrophication affects an aquatic ecosystem.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Excess nitrates/phosphates from fertiliser runoff enter waterways (1). Algae grow rapidly (algal bloom) blocking light to submerged plants (1). Plants and then algae die; decomposing bacteria increase in number (1). Aerobic decomposition uses up dissolved oxygen causing fish and other aerobic organisms to die (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the population estimate using Lincoln Index if 40 animals were caught and marked, then in a second sample of 50, 8 were marked.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'N = (n1 × n2) / nm = (40 × 50) / 8 (1) = 250 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why biodiversity tends to increase during succession.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'As succession progresses the habitat becomes more complex with more layers and microhabitats creating more niches (1). More niches support more species; soil develops and conditions moderate allowing a wider range of organisms to establish (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the carbon cycle, including the role of respiration and photosynthesis.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Photosynthesis removes CO2 from the atmosphere fixing it into organic molecules in plants (1). Respiration by all organisms returns CO2 to the atmosphere by oxidising organic molecules (1). Decomposition of dead organisms releases CO2 through microbial respiration (1). Combustion of fossil fuels (stored carbon from ancient organisms) also releases CO2 rapidly (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of denitrifying bacteria in the nitrogen cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Denitrifying bacteria convert nitrate (NO3-) to nitrogen gas (N2) (1). They are anaerobic and operate in waterlogged soils; this removes available nitrogen from the soil returning it to the atmosphere (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why farmers may wish to reduce denitrification in their soil.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Denitrification removes nitrate from soil making it unavailable for crop uptake (1). Farmers can reduce it by improving drainage to keep soil aerobic since denitrifying bacteria are anaerobic (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how conservation measures can maintain biodiversity.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Protected areas/nature reserves prevent habitat destruction and disturbance (1). Controlled grazing or mowing can maintain specific seral stages with high diversity (deflected succession) (1). Breeding programmes for endangered species maintain genetic diversity; seed banks preserve plant genetic resources (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by deflected succession and give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Deflected succession occurs when human activity prevents a community from reaching its natural climax (1). Example: mowing/grazing grassland prevents woodland developing keeping it as species-rich grassland (a plagioclimax) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why monocultures reduce biodiversity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Monocultures are large areas of a single crop species providing very few different habitats/niches (1). This supports fewer species; pesticides and herbicides further reduce populations of insects, weeds, and associated organisms (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe two assumptions of the mark-release-recapture method.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'No immigration/emigration/births/deaths between sampling events so population size is stable (1). Marking does not affect survival or behaviour and marked individuals mix randomly with the population (1).'},
      {q: 'Calculate the Simpson\'s Index of Diversity for an area with 3 species: species A (30 individuals), species B (15), species C (5).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'N = 50. (n/N)² for A = (30/50)² = 0.36; B = (15/50)² = 0.09; C = (5/50)² = 0.01 (1). Sum = 0.36 + 0.09 + 0.01 = 0.46 (1). D = 1 - 0.46 = 0.54 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why sustainable management of fish stocks requires limiting catches.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'If more fish are caught than can be replaced by reproduction the population declines (1). Catch limits (quotas) and minimum mesh sizes allow populations to maintain breeding numbers ensuring long-term availability of the resource (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of Rhizobium bacteria in the nitrogen cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Rhizobium are nitrogen-fixing bacteria that live in root nodules of leguminous plants in a mutualistic relationship (1). They convert atmospheric N2 to NH3/NH4+ which the plant can use to make amino acids; in return the bacteria receive sugars/carbohydrates (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why food chains rarely have more than five trophic levels.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Only about 10% of energy is transferred between each level (1). After 4-5 transfers there is insufficient energy remaining to support another trophic level / the biomass available is too small (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the greenhouse effect and explain how human activity enhances it.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Short-wave solar radiation passes through the atmosphere and warms the Earth; the Earth re-radiates long-wave (infrared) radiation (1). Greenhouse gases (CO2, methane, N2O) absorb and re-emit some of this radiation back to Earth warming the surface (1). Burning fossil fuels, deforestation, and intensive farming increase greenhouse gas concentrations enhancing warming beyond natural levels (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between a habitat and a niche.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A habitat is the place where an organism lives (its physical environment) (1). A niche is the role of an organism in its ecosystem including what it eats, when it is active, its interactions with other species, and its habitat requirements (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how abiotic factors can affect population size.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Abiotic factors like temperature, light, water availability, and pH affect metabolic rate, reproduction, and survival (1). If conditions become unfavourable (e.g. drought) death rate increases and birth rate decreases reducing population size (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why biological control is considered more sustainable than chemical pesticides.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Biological control uses natural predators/parasites that are self-sustaining and do not need repeated application (1). Unlike pesticides they do not accumulate in food chains (bioaccumulation) or harm non-target organisms (1). However they may be less effective immediately and can be difficult to control if the introduced organism affects non-target species (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the process of ammonification.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Decomposers/saprobionts break down proteins and nucleic acids in dead organisms and excretory waste (1). They release ammonium ions (NH4+) into the soil which can then be nitrified or taken up by plants (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why removing hedgerows from farmland reduces biodiversity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Hedgerows provide habitats, food sources, nesting sites, and wildlife corridors for many species (1). Removing them eliminates these niches and fragments remaining habitats isolating populations (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why pyramids of biomass are generally more accurate than pyramids of numbers.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Pyramids of numbers can be inverted if producers are very large (e.g. one tree supporting many insects) (1). Pyramids of biomass account for the mass/size of organisms giving a more realistic picture of energy stored at each level (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the effect of deforestation on the carbon cycle.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Trees are major carbon sinks; removing them means less CO2 is removed from the atmosphere by photosynthesis (1). Burning felled trees releases stored carbon as CO2 directly (1). Decomposition of remaining roots/leaf litter increases soil microbial respiration releasing more CO2 (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how nitrogen enters food chains.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Plants absorb nitrate ions (NO3-) from soil through roots by active transport (1). Nitrate is used to make amino acids (combined with organic molecules from photosynthesis) and then proteins/DNA (1). Animals obtain nitrogen by eating plants or other animals; nitrogen passes through the food chain (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why conservation of genetic diversity within a species is important.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Genetic diversity provides the variation needed for natural selection if the environment changes (1). Without genetic diversity a population cannot adapt and is more vulnerable to extinction from disease or environmental change (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how you would use a transect to study the distribution of organisms across a habitat.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Lay a line/tape from one area to another across the environmental gradient (1). Place quadrats at regular intervals along the line (systematic sampling) or at random points (1). Record species and abundance at each point and relate distribution to abiotic factors measured at each position (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the net productivity of a climax community approaches zero.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In a climax community total community respiration uses almost all the energy fixed by photosynthesis (GPP ≈ R) (1). Very little new biomass accumulates because energy input is balanced by energy losses in respiration maintaining stable biomass (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of saprobionts in an ecosystem.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Saprobionts secrete enzymes onto dead organic material digesting it externally (extracellular digestion) (1). They absorb the soluble products for their own metabolism while releasing inorganic minerals back into the soil for recycling (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the impact of increasing atmospheric CO2 on global ecosystems.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Increased CO2 enhances the greenhouse effect raising global temperatures (1). This can shift climate zones affecting species distribution and causing loss of habitat (e.g. coral bleaching, ice cap melting) (1). Changed rainfall patterns and extreme weather events disrupt food webs and ecosystem stability (1).'},
      {q: 'A farmer adds nitrogen fertiliser to a field. Explain how this increases crop yield.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Nitrogen is needed for amino acid/protein and nucleotide/DNA synthesis essential for plant growth (1). Fertiliser provides readily available nitrate replacing minerals removed by harvesting so growth is not limited by nitrogen supply (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why overuse of fertiliser can be counterproductive and harmful.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Excess fertiliser is leached from soil into waterways causing eutrophication (1). This kills aquatic organisms and can make water undrinkable; it also wastes money and does not further increase crop growth beyond the nutrient optimum (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of mutualism in the nitrogen cycle with reference to legumes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Rhizobium bacteria in root nodules of legumes fix atmospheric N2 into NH3 which the plant uses (1). In return the plant provides the bacteria with carbohydrates (sugars) from photosynthesis; both organisms benefit (mutualism) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by a keystone species.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A keystone species has a disproportionately large effect on its ecosystem relative to its abundance (1). Its removal would cause significant changes to community structure and potentially loss of many other species (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how intensive farming increases net productivity available to humans.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Pesticides remove organisms that consume crop biomass directing more energy to the crop/humans (1). Fertilisers remove mineral limitation and selective breeding/irrigation maximise photosynthesis increasing the proportion of GPP converted to harvestable biomass (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why scientists use models to predict population changes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Models incorporate birth rate, death rate, immigration, and emigration along with environmental factors to predict future population trends (1). They help plan conservation strategies and manage resources but are simplified representations that may not account for all variables or unpredictable events (1).'}
    ]
  },
  'T8': {
    name: 'Control of Gene Expression',
    questions: [
      {q: 'State what is meant by a proto-oncogene.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A normal gene that codes for proteins promoting cell division/growth; when mutated it becomes an oncogene (1).'},
      {q: 'Name the type of gene that normally prevents uncontrolled cell division.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Tumour suppressor gene (1).'},
      {q: 'State what is meant by totipotency.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The ability of a cell to differentiate into any cell type of the organism including extraembryonic tissue (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of DNA methylation in gene expression.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Methyl groups are added to cytosine bases in DNA (often at CpG sites near promoters) (1). This silences/prevents transcription by preventing transcription factor binding or recruiting proteins that condense chromatin (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how histone acetylation increases gene expression.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Acetyl groups added to histone tails reduce the positive charge on histones (1). This loosens the association between histones and DNA making it more accessible to RNA polymerase and transcription factors (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the structure of an operon.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A cluster of structural genes that are transcribed together as a single mRNA (1). Preceded by a promoter (where RNA polymerase binds) and an operator (regulatory region) (1). A separate regulatory gene codes for a repressor protein that can bind to the operator (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how the lac operon is switched on in the presence of lactose.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'When lactose is present it binds to the repressor protein (acting as an inducer) (1). This changes the repressor shape so it can no longer bind to the operator (1). RNA polymerase can now bind to the promoter and transcribe the structural genes producing beta-galactosidase and permease (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe one use of PCR.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'PCR amplifies small amounts of DNA to produce millions of copies (1). Used in forensics (DNA profiling from crime scenes), medical diagnosis (detecting pathogens), or research (producing enough DNA for sequencing/cloning) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the three stages of PCR.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Denaturation (95°C): hydrogen bonds break separating DNA into single strands (1). Annealing (50-65°C): primers bind to complementary sequences on the template strands (1). Extension (72°C): Taq polymerase adds complementary nucleotides extending from the primers to synthesise new strands (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why restriction enzymes that produce sticky ends are preferred in genetic engineering.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Sticky ends are short single-stranded overhangs with exposed bases (1). They can form complementary base pairs with sticky ends cut by the same enzyme from another DNA source allowing fragments to join together (annealed by DNA ligase) (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how gel electrophoresis separates DNA fragments.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'DNA fragments are placed in wells in an agarose gel and an electric field is applied (1). DNA is negatively charged (phosphate groups) so fragments move toward the positive electrode (1). Smaller fragments move faster/further through the gel pores than larger ones separating by size (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why all body cells have the same genome but different cell types express different genes.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'All cells arise from the same zygote by mitosis so contain identical DNA (1). During development transcription factors activate/repress specific genes in each cell type (1). Epigenetic modifications (methylation, histone modification) stably silence genes not needed in that cell type making differentiation permanent (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe one ethical concern with genetic engineering of crops.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Transgenes could spread to wild populations via cross-pollination potentially creating herbicide-resistant weeds (1). There are concerns about unforeseen ecological effects and corporate control over food supply through patenting of GM organisms (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the difference between somatic and germline gene therapy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Somatic gene therapy targets body cells only; effects are not inherited by offspring (1). Germline gene therapy targets reproductive/embryonic cells; changes are passed to all future generations (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how genetic fingerprinting works.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'DNA is extracted and specific regions (STRs/VNTRs) are amplified by PCR (1). DNA is cut with restriction enzymes and separated by gel electrophoresis (1). Fragments are transferred to a nylon membrane (Southern blot) and radioactive/fluorescent probes bind to specific sequences (1). The pattern of bands is unique to each individual (except identical twins) and can be used for identification or paternity testing (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how RNA interference (RNAi) silences gene expression.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Double-stranded RNA is processed into small interfering RNA (siRNA) by the enzyme Dicer (1). siRNA binds to the RISC complex which uses one strand to find complementary mRNA (1). The target mRNA is degraded preventing translation and silencing the gene (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why epigenetic changes are important during development.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'They allow cells with the same DNA to differentiate into different cell types by selectively activating/silencing genes (1). Epigenetic patterns are maintained through cell division ensuring daughter cells retain their specialised function (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of a vector in genetic engineering.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A vector (e.g. plasmid, virus) carries the gene of interest into a host cell (1). It contains a promoter for expression, an origin of replication, and selectable markers (e.g. antibiotic resistance) to identify successful transformants (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why cancer usually requires multiple mutations.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A single mutation is usually insufficient to cause cancer due to multiple control mechanisms (1). Mutations must accumulate in both oncogenes (gain of function) and tumour suppressor genes (loss of function) to override normal growth controls (1). This multi-step process explains why cancer risk increases with age as mutations accumulate over time (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) are produced.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Adult differentiated cells (e.g. skin fibroblasts) are reprogrammed by introducing specific transcription factors (e.g. Oct4, Sox2, Klf4, c-Myc) (1). These factors reverse epigenetic modifications restoring pluripotency so cells can differentiate into many cell types (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain one advantage of using iPSCs over embryonic stem cells.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'iPSCs are produced from the patient\'s own cells avoiding immune rejection when used in therapy (1). Their use avoids the ethical issues of destroying embryos to obtain stem cells (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how Taq polymerase differs from normal DNA polymerase and why this matters for PCR.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Taq polymerase is thermostable (from thermophilic bacteria) so it is not denatured at 95°C denaturation step (1). Normal DNA polymerase would be destroyed at this temperature and would need to be added fresh each cycle making PCR impractical (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the two-hit hypothesis of cancer development.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Tumour suppressor genes have two copies (one on each homologous chromosome) (1). Both alleles must be inactivated (by mutation, deletion, or methylation) for loss of tumour suppression; one functional copy is sufficient for normal cell cycle control (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe one application of gene probes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A labelled single-stranded DNA/RNA sequence complementary to the gene of interest is used (1). It binds by complementary base pairing to locate a specific gene in a sample (e.g. diagnosis of genetic disorders, identifying transgenic organisms) (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how CRISPR-Cas9 works for gene editing.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A guide RNA is designed complementary to the target DNA sequence (1). The guide RNA directs the Cas9 nuclease enzyme to the precise location in the genome (1). Cas9 cuts both strands of DNA at that site; the cell\'s repair mechanisms can then delete/insert/replace sequences at the cut site (1).'},
      {q: 'State two ethical issues with CRISPR gene editing in humans.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Germline editing could create heritable changes passed to future generations who cannot consent (1). Potential for use in enhancement rather than treatment (designer babies) raises concerns about equality and eugenics (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why alternative splicing increases protein diversity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Different combinations of exons from the same pre-mRNA can be joined together (1). This means one gene can code for multiple different mRNA sequences and therefore multiple different proteins with different functions (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the process of transformation in genetic engineering.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Host cells (usually bacteria) are made competent to take up foreign DNA (e.g. by heat shock or CaCl2 treatment) (1). Recombinant plasmids are mixed with cells and some bacteria take up the plasmid incorporating the gene of interest (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how antibiotic resistance genes are used as markers in genetic engineering.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The vector contains an antibiotic resistance gene as a selectable marker (1). After transformation cells are grown on agar containing the antibiotic; only cells that have taken up the plasmid survive and grow forming colonies (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how a microarray (gene chip) works.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Thousands of known DNA sequences (probes) are fixed in specific positions on a chip (1). mRNA from the test cells is converted to cDNA and labelled with fluorescent dye (1). Labelled cDNA is washed over the chip; it hybridises to complementary probes and fluorescence shows which genes are being expressed (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why post-transcriptional modifications are necessary before mRNA leaves the nucleus.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Introns (non-coding sequences) must be removed by splicing to produce a continuous coding sequence (1). A 5\' cap and 3\' poly-A tail are added to protect mRNA from degradation by nucleases (1). These modifications also aid ribosome recognition and initiation of translation in the cytoplasm (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why environmental factors can cause epigenetic changes that affect health.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Diet, stress, toxins (e.g. cigarette smoke) can alter DNA methylation patterns or histone modifications (1). These changes can silence tumour suppressor genes or activate oncogenes contributing to cancer risk (1). Some epigenetic changes can be passed to daughter cells (mitotically) and potentially to offspring affecting long-term health (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how gene therapy could treat cystic fibrosis.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A functional copy of the CFTR gene is inserted into a vector (e.g. liposome or adenovirus) (1). The vector delivers the gene to lung epithelial cells (e.g. via nasal spray/inhaler) (1). The functional CFTR protein is produced allowing normal chloride ion transport and reducing mucus viscosity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why gene therapy for cystic fibrosis needs to be repeated.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Lung epithelial cells are continuously replaced from stem cells that still carry the faulty gene (1). The therapeutic gene is not permanently integrated into the genome so new cells do not express it, requiring repeated treatments (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the role of DNA ligase in genetic engineering.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'DNA ligase forms phosphodiester bonds between the sugar-phosphate backbones of DNA fragments (1). It seals the gaps between the inserted gene and the vector DNA creating a continuous recombinant DNA molecule (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why fluorescent markers are useful in genetic engineering.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fluorescent marker genes (e.g. GFP) are inserted alongside the gene of interest in the vector (1). Cells that glow under UV light have successfully taken up and expressed the recombinant DNA making identification easy without killing cells (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain how knowledge of epigenetics could lead to new cancer treatments.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'In cancer, tumour suppressor genes may be silenced by hypermethylation (1). Drugs that inhibit DNA methyltransferases could reactivate these genes restoring cell cycle control (1). Similarly HDAC inhibitors increase acetylation re-opening chromatin at silenced genes; these epigenetic drugs are reversible unlike genetic mutations (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how stem cells could be used to treat spinal cord injuries.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Pluripotent/multipotent stem cells can be directed to differentiate into neurones or glial cells (1). These could replace damaged nerve cells and potentially restore connections in the spinal cord, reversing paralysis (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why identical twins may develop different diseases despite having the same DNA.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Different environmental exposures throughout life cause different epigenetic modifications (methylation/acetylation patterns) (1). These alter gene expression differently in each twin, making one susceptible to disease while the other remains healthy (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain the role of transcription factors in cell differentiation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Transcription factors activate or repress specific genes by binding to promoter/enhancer regions (1). Different combinations of transcription factors in different cells determine which genes are expressed, driving differentiation into specialised cell types (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe one risk of using viral vectors in gene therapy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The virus may insert the therapeutic gene into the middle of an existing gene (insertional mutagenesis) (1). This could disrupt a tumour suppressor gene or activate an oncogene potentially causing cancer (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain what is meant by recombinant DNA.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Recombinant DNA is DNA that has been artificially constructed by combining genetic material from two or more different organisms (1). It is created by inserting a gene from one organism into a vector DNA molecule (e.g. a plasmid) using restriction enzymes and ligase (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why the Human Genome Project was significant for medicine.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'It identified all human genes allowing identification of genes associated with genetic diseases (1). This enables genetic testing/screening for inherited conditions and identification of drug targets (1). Pharmacogenomics can now tailor drug treatments to individual genetic profiles improving efficacy and reducing side effects (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe one practical application of genetic fingerprinting.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Forensic identification: DNA from a crime scene can be matched to a suspect by comparing STR band patterns (1). Each person (except identical twins) has a unique pattern so a match provides strong evidence of identity (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why off-target effects are a concern with CRISPR-Cas9.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The guide RNA may bind to DNA sequences similar (but not identical) to the target elsewhere in the genome (1). Cas9 could cut at these unintended sites causing insertions, deletions, or rearrangements with potentially harmful effects including cancer (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe how monoclonal antibodies can be used as a targeted cancer treatment.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Monoclonal antibodies are produced to recognise specific antigens on cancer cell surfaces (1). They can be conjugated to drugs/toxins/radioactive markers delivering treatment directly to cancer cells (1). This reduces damage to healthy cells compared to conventional chemotherapy (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why understanding gene regulation is important for treating genetic diseases.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Many diseases result from incorrect gene expression rather than absent genes (1). If scientists understand how genes are regulated (transcription factors, epigenetics, RNAi) they can develop treatments that switch genes on/off without replacing the gene itself (1).'},
      {q: 'Describe the difference between in vivo and ex vivo gene therapy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In vivo: the vector carrying the therapeutic gene is delivered directly to the patient\'s body (e.g. inhaled to lungs) (1). Ex vivo: cells are removed from the patient, the gene is inserted in the laboratory, and corrected cells are returned to the patient (1).'},
      {q: 'Explain why genetic engineering of insulin-producing bacteria was a major medical advance.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Human insulin gene inserted into bacteria allows large-scale production of human insulin (1). This replaced animal insulin (from pigs/cows) which could cause allergic reactions and was limited in supply; recombinant insulin is identical to human insulin and available in unlimited quantities (1).'}
    ]
  }
};

if (typeof module !== 'undefined' && module.exports) {
  module.exports = { BIOLOGY_AQA_PRACTICE };
}
